We want to compare how well a large-scale language model (LLM) internally structures and stores knowledge through a knowledge graph (KG).
A knowledge graph typically represents knowledge in the form of a triple [format: subject -> relation -> object].
Where a relation is one of the following lists:

- created
- dealsWith
- diedIn
- directed
- edited
- exports
- graduatedFrom
- happenedIn
- hasAcademicAdvisor

- created
- dealsWith

- edited

- graduatedFrom

- hasAcademicAdvisor

A knowledge graph typically represents knowledge in the form of a triple [format: subject -> relation -> object].
Where a relation is one of the following lists:
- actedIn
- created
- dealsWith
- diedIn

We want to compare how well a large-scale language model (LLM) internally structures and stores knowledge through a knowledge graph (KG).
A knowledge graph typically represents knowledge in the form of a triple [format: subject -> relation -> object].
Where a relation is one of the following lists:
- actedIn
- created
- dealsWith
- diedIn
- directed
- edited
- exports
- graduatedFrom
- happenedIn
- hasAcademicAdvisor
- hasCapital
- hasChild
- hasCurrency
- hasGender
- hasMusicalRole
- hasNeighbor
- hasOfficialLanguage
- hasWebsite
- hasWonPrize
- imports
- influences
- isAffiliatedTo
- isCitizenOf
- isConnectedTo
- isInterestedIn
- isKnownFor
- isLeaderOf
- isLocatedIn
- isMarriedTo
- isPoliticianOf
- livesIn
- owns
- participatedIn
- playsFor
- wasBornIn
- worksAt
- wroteMusicFor

Here are some demo examples of such a knowledge graph.

<BEGIN_OF_DEMO_EXAMPLE>
* Target entity: Plumb_(singer)

We want to compare how well a large-scale language model (LLM) internally structures and stores knowledge through a knowledge graph (KG).
A knowledge graph typically represents knowledge in the form of a triple [format: subject -> relation -> object].
Where a relation is one of the following lists:
- actedIn
- created
- dealsWith
- diedIn
- directed
- edited
- exports
- graduatedFrom

A knowledge graph typically represents knowledge in the form of a triple [format: subject -> relation -> object].
Where a relation is one of the following lists:
- actedIn
- created
- dealsWith
- diedIn
- directed
- edited
- exports
- graduatedFrom
- happenedIn
- hasAcademicAdvisor
- hasCapital
- hasChild
- hasCurrency
- hasGender
- hasMusicalRole
- hasNeighbor
- hasOfficialLanguage
- hasWebsite
- hasWonPrize
- imports
- influences
- isAffiliatedTo
- isCitizenOf
- isConnectedTo
- isInterestedIn
- isKnownFor
- isLeaderOf
- isLocatedIn
- isMarriedTo
- isPoliticianOf
- livesIn
- owns
- participatedIn
- playsFor
- wasBornIn
- worksAt
- wroteMusicFor
